AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: hi everyone  scott here. i’m excited to join and discover how i can best use my skillset to help build on ocean’s vision. i work in product development/management and recently negotiated and implemented a $6.5m usd development contract with over 40 developers and designers.   i’m eager to build products and am open to submitting a proposal for review but don’t yet have a strong use case. i’ve been speaking with @mark about the positioning/business strategy with ocean and keen to explore this topic in more detail. we collaborated on a question for the community below:

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: the objective of this question is to get a clear understanding of the unique value proposition of ocean so that we can better serve  and strategically implement ocean protocol’s vision in the market.   as we understand  the ocean protocol is ultimately a 2 sided marketplace connecting buyers and sellers of data. one could have a popular dataset on an ocean market which generates $500 000 in revenue and another person may have 500 datasets on ocean market generating $0 in revenue based on the demand for their data assets.   it’s possible (but unlikely) that i am going to receive a lot of money for sharing my personal location data. even in the best case scenario i may generate a few $100 dollars which some may find attractive but most will encounter too much friction/hesitation towards opening up and sharing their personal data for some relatively small sum of money. (this may not be the case in all situations/countries as a few hundred dollars will be a lot of money but in those cases the buying power of that consumer base would be lower and therefore the incentive for businesses to leverage that data would be lower also).

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: therefore  the higher value datasets for ocean are likely those held in big privately held databases or brokered in other partnering models like: www.datarade.ai which could:     1.    benefit from being used in machine learning algorithms  ai etc to create value (i.e. there is demand for the data).       2.    be sold to the market without the company receiving a significant backlash from existing customers/business partners/shareholders i.e. the benefits of enabling access to the data (revenues generated) outweigh the costs of providing secure access to the data for the market to consume. one could imagine a backlash against a local retailer if customers discovered that all of a sudden their shopping data was being sold by the retailer for profit.  this is where we start to get a little stuck… if there is huge revenue potential sitting behind closed doors (in privately held databases)  then why wouldn’t a more traditional private company have come along and given the owners of these datasets the ability to compute against the datasets privately? is this the secret sauce that’s only enabled through ocean protocol?  if not  then is it the open  networked and decentralised nature of the ocean protocol? under this assumption we are assuming that an open  networked and decentralised org structure is the superior org structure for executing on this opportunity.   it would be great to better understand this topic so that we can more accurately convey the usp to the market. knowing the answer to this should also help indicate where to start looking for new business opportunities with ocean.

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: the secret sauce part with compute to data is one important factor but the other factor that makes ocean standout is the pricing mechanism of the assets. this expands ocean from being a two sided market to much more. the stakers become a part of the market as well. they curate  price and validate datasets but also benefit from that.  the combination of these features makes ocean a 🦄.  i am very open to have sessions with you and @mark to discuss this further and create an overview and analysis paper.

AUTHOR: Frederic#8800
CONTENT: (damn  robin was already here while i was typing 😄 as always 🚀 👏🏼 )  hi scott! these are super valuable thoughts. thanks for sharing! the answer includes my personal perspective  there is potentially a lot more  but this is what is important in my opinion:  with compute-to-data you can sell data access without having the problems you mentioned. if set up correctly  there is no “backslash” from customers/business partners/shareholders because the data is never moved  data consumers never see the data itself.  still  you (and any buyer) can generate insights on private data in a fully compliant way. this includes machine learning  business analytics  or other forms of data aggregation. it’s not about the data owner who can compute here. it’s about any potential buyer. and because ocean is permissionless  this could be anyone.  as you say  this is a risk/reward trade-off. and the more sensitive the data  the more security you need to balance the risk.   data monetization makes sense for traditional companies in many cases  even when companies compete. mobi is an example where traditional automakers can potentially share datasets for autonomous driving (without giving away the data) to compete with tesla. in other cases  data can be a “byproduct” of a companies core business. in this case  it’s only a cost-center and they could start monetizing it. compared to what is on the market right now  c2d is more about huge and valuable datasets. there are many similar examples we could think of.  “turn your data storage into a profit center” (while keeping ownership and full control and being compliant) is one of the opportunities here.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: hi @robin | dataunion   @frederic and @kaimeinke thank you for your thoughts.  the pricing mechanism is definitely an interesting feature and one where the incentives that exist would probably be harder to replicate in a private model (in my head i keep comparing this to a private venture  not to discredit the ocean project but to instead uncover the unique benefits of op). staking tokens on datasets encourages market participants to curate good data and send a signal to the market that ‘this is good data’ which is great.   open and permissionless access to data for c2d applications to run on is also another great benefit. assuming this means that some people (with good intentions!) are accessing datasets they couldn’t otherwise access through other third party providers already.   data unions and shared data initiatives (like scanning bills and monetising as a group) is also a unique and interesting concept. in theory i could probably start something like that today (as a private venture) but be subject to a number of local laws and regulations (friction) and so doing something like this on op where the incentives are closer to the consumer than they maybe are in a private model could be a unique benefit.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: thinking these scenarios through is starting to lead me down the path of… maybe the networked  permissionless and incentive based model is a fundamentally superior model for mass scale than a private model. i.e. a private company can only hire so quickly  expand into new markets so quickly and jump on new trends so quickly. in other words it can only spread its incentives so thinly before it runs out.   op (and other decentralised projects for that matter) are more organic and take on a life of their own. as they are open and permissionless  anyone can jump on board  have a go  at no cost to the overarching entity (op) i.e  not many people are spending their spare time thinking up new ways for jeff bezos to grow his empire - he has to employ people to do that for him.   therefore  those that jump on board and build things the market wants are rewarded and those that don’t  simply try again or fade away. the equivalent would be trying to convince a bunch of investors to invest in a private company where we will pay anyone who walks in through the door to do stuff and some will succeed and others will fail but we don’t really know what’s going to happen. 😆   i feel like i’ve either gone on a complete tangent or am touching on something fundamentally important?

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: bruce said at some point that amms and accompanying dexs are already providing a ton of savings as such a service in the traditional finance world would cost 50k+$ - in web3 less than 500$.  the same is true for hiring  payments  authenticating and outreach in the web3 space. wallets and the options that are attached to them are a powerful tool.  i think the savings and the faster verification of ideas is an important point.

AUTHOR: .scottm3
CONTENT: thanks again @robin | dataunion and @kaimeinke i think this gives me enough to go on for now at least! in terms of next steps it might be worth putting all of this thinking together into a document/blog post and share it here for review before publishing.

AUTHOR: carmina19
CONTENT: hello @everyone product | compute-to-data has landed in #oceanmarket! it enables buying & selling of private data while preserving privacy. ctd resolves the tradeoff between the benefits of using private data & the risks of exposing it. full overview: https://blog.oceanprotocol.com/compute-to-data-is-now-available-in-ocean-market-58868be52ef7 #theyearofscaling  "with compute-to-data  data never leaves its owner’s premises.  • data owners can monetize data while preserving privacy & control • yet data buyers can create value from it with analytics  ai modeling & more  🌊 all via the ocean market interface. try it: https://market.oceanprotocol.com/"  "ctd benefits ai practitioners: • they can access valuable  private data that was previously unavailable  which can lead to more accurate ai models. and w/o liability – they don’t see the data. • they can also publish & monetize their algorithms. these can even stay private (!)"  "businesses and entrepreneurs can quickly launch their own ocean-powered data marketplace for their vertical.   ocean compute-to-data helps them further preserve their sellers’ privacy  and support more compute & ai flows."  "here’s a technical overview of ocean compute-to-data: https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/concepts/compute-to-data  and here’s how to write algorithms for it: https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/tutorials/compute-to-data-algorithms/"  "ctd in ocean market is a major milestone in our 2021 roadmap & a big step towards our vision of data as a new asset class📍  https://oceanprotocol.com/technology/roadmap  we invite you to try out ctd  to explore  to stress-test  and to tell us how it goes! we welcome all feedback 💬"

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: hi everyone   as some of you may know i will have limited capacity to lead the ocean ambassador program over the next few weeks for personal reasons. during that time  the critical activities i was involved in will be covered by fellow senior ambassadors.   - @zippy1979 will take care of budget and finances. this process should move to activity farming and be managed as a team as early as february. in the meantime  upkar will be in charge of validating with ambassadors that they have completed their work  and preparing the list of payouts in ocean to ambassadors.    upkar will also be the interim program lead  dealing with program improvements  being the liaison with the rest of the ecosystem  managing weekly updates in the oceandao meeting (this should be taken in turns by different ambassadors)  and ensuring things run smoothly overall.  - @andrea | ocean protocol will be the community & activity lead  managing our group  the onboarding of new ambassadors and managing/coordinating the work of ambassadors to ensure quality and timely deliveries.  - @robin | dataunion will prepare the grant proposal for oceandao r14  and keep co-approving transactions with me from our gnosis safe.  responsibilities and work in different wgs should be unaffected. i may have more time to allocate to the program than i anticipate  but i prefer to plan for the worst case and ensure that we have the right level of support for the group at all time.

CONTENT: hello guys  at the #🪢︱ambassadors   looking forward to some review of the indian ocean outreach program.   https://indian-ocean.gitbook.io/indian-ocean-outreach-program/  this essentially covers the roadmap and activities that we have set out to complete by end of this month.  would be nice to have some feedback before i accelerate on a few promo activities. we have also placed a program in the name of 'indian ocean' ambassadors  who also have to complete the ocean academy. the aim is to have a lot of funneling outreach through the ambassadors from now on. we were glad to onboard @gyan | starknet foundation/tpg as one of our first ambassadors through both academy as well as through the google form that we have mentioned in the gitbook.  on a high-level  expecting some feedback on  - overall information flow - is it sufficient? giving a good intel of what's been played out so far? - how the specific ambassador program google form looks in line with ocean 101 activities? - we have not really decided on any promo-based activities yet for indian ambassadors  but we will be sourcing it completely from the budget reserved for us during the r10 budget.  - any other feedback that can help us?  **on a parallel note:** we are also working on a few workshop initiatives that will help folks convert better for the ocean academy that is often regarded as 'too heavy' for complete beginners. we intend to follow the process  but would be happy to receive some feedback on all the above. in the future we also plan to work on some materials that will help people understand the ocean academy better. the following article is an example of that.  https://medium.com/@indianoceandao/ocean-academy-guest-review-series-1f224e162f5b

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: can you provide some data/insight/clarity on the "sentiment" you reference to? the point is quite unspecific ..  re recruitment  here is how i view things overall: - if we are talking about ocean ambassadors  then you should leverage the process @andrea | ocean protocol is finalizing. there is a reason why ocean101 and the pledge have been set as requirements. we want the ambassadors to hold to the highest standards in quality and ethics. - if we are talking about members of a network of ocean stakeholders for india  you can do whatever you want; you may fork anything that we did  it's all open source and shared with the community for that purpose.  i'll dive into the doc later anyways so i can have more precise feedback as well.

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: nothing is set in stone  at the moment.   - as admittedly it's in a feedback phase at the moment and if there are any red-flags  would be happy to address it before venturing into any promos/activities (that we are deciding in line with a final hackathon that is planned towards the end of jan)  - in it's current format. we are trying to get them through the google form  so the cta leads them to relevant channels with questions resolved through us. think of us as more of a guides/helping hands than any sort of gatekeepers/a deciding authority as far as the main ambassador wg is concerned. so this would not interfere with @andrea | ocean protocol responsibilities at the moment.  folks who remain committed to just the indian outreach would remain on our socials.  - we may have an increase in the number of ambassadors coming from the indian community and the aim is to have a cta that bring them here  either   a) directly to the wg channel b) also get the relatively live support through our telegram/discord channels that we have provided on our linktree having the socials   - in terms of insights  it is still an open sentiment; that i had also gathered from @gyan | starknet foundation/tpg who completed the academy successfully  who believes in the program and has suggestions to improve it so we can have motivated members as ambassadors while complying with the pledge. so this was not an insight that was completely based on folks who have not looked to commit to the ambassadorship  yet. i hope that clarifies.

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: good morning @everyone  hope you all had a great we!  ☀️  quick update to keep you in the loop! 🚀   as most of you may have realised from the ambassadors telegram group q4/2021 saw a lot of planning and strategising. the vision of the ambassador program is to build an impactful global team that supports the growth of the ocean protocol ecosystem worldwide and  in order to achieve this  the program needs to be well structured to welcome dozens  if not hundreds  of new ambassadors from each part of the world. ambassadors are now working hard to complete their tasks on time. the new program will be ready by end of this month and today we're sharing what will be its core: a brand new **activity farming and rewards system.**    **activity farming**. this is a list of activities that you as an ambassador can pick from and start working on anytime. https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1r-ng2vjvicg_a3cuk9fph2queaoyzhrwnyzyhvouu4m/edit?usp=sharing once you find the activity you like and you are ready to start  add a trello card with the name of the activity under the “active” column.    - **rewards system**. we have introduced a mix of basic rewards and performance rewards to promote fairness  transparency  and to incentivise high-quality works.  base rewards are distributed at the end of each month upon meeting the minimum requirements  whilst performance rewards will be distributed upon meeting the predetermined targets at the end of the relevant period.   note:  if you would like to propose an initiative not present in the activity farming list  please add a trello card in the “activities awaiting confirmation” column and share details such as objectives  rewards request  eta. your initiative will then be evaluated by the ap team.   the activity farming list is a living document  it will be reviewed monthly and improved as the program grows. we always welcome suggestions  so please share feedback by adding your comments in the google docs.  happy farming! 🧑‍🌾 ❤️

CONTENT: hi drprk  thanks for sharing the gitbook and the medium article. i've checked them out and would have a few points of feedback: 1)    the gitbook was a great idea  and it looks awesome. the indian program is delivering on its objectives  which is excellent for everyone in the ecosystem! 2)    handling ambassador recruitment through the gitbook makes sense to build a vibrant indian community  but it is not appropriate to recruit “ocean ambassadors” in my opinion. why do i say that?  a.    because the ocean ambassadors have nearly completed a revamp of the onboarding process  and once the ambassador website will be up  the gitbook will be redundant. i would personally avoid duplicating processes/adding complexity and potential confusion for new ambassadors.  b.    and because if we use the same process to recruit new members for different groups  we may end up facing unnecessary and unwishful competition across ‘branches’ of the program.  c.    finally  it could make sense to consider regional programs as standalone programs  that are not affiliated with the general ambassador group. all would meet and interact in a new outreach wg  which i understand is in the process of being created. that’d be a great way to federate  share best practices and content  and loosely coordinate across all country programs  including japan  turkey  greece  nigeria  india  ..etc.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: 3)    great article on ocean academy. having workshops on top is indeed helpful. it may need to be updated soon as we fine tune the launch of ocean academy v2  which was planned for end dec ’21  but will be shipped end jan ‘22. here is the updated flow and content that i’m currently migrating to github: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rzaz5aa9axjt6ygjgshtigtk9ambl4pdphxud-vjhog/edit?usp=sharing   the content is easier to understand/digest  and is organized in a more logical flow for newcomers. in addition  the front-end + back-end have been updated and will be deployed at the same time as the content  so the user experience will be greatly improved with this v2.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: ocean academy may be further improved  of course. any specific observations  thoughts and feedback are good to take!

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: super thanks for the feedback and for your time that you've taken @lrt 🙌   1 & 2) will go through with the feedback with some more considerations. i will also convey them to @andrea | ocean protocol   i had a call earlier today where i expressed that the ambassador 'program' per se will be an effective add-on with funneling mechanisms & remove duplicity  with more focus on managing traffic henceforth. i will work on your feedback and pass onto andrea as well so it's in line with the revamped process.   **but** i see why you mention that they need not be recruited. i will see if the google form can be sunset with a different mechanism in place  adding redundant process can affect the ux of the general program. rebranding it slightly different will be helpful in context of outreach.  c) the outreach wg makes sense  will be a great place to have the processes separate from the ambassador program in general.  3) thanks for the feedback. workshops will be planned in tandem with feedback on the process of v2 version of the academy as well. i will check the updated flow before discussing this again while planning the academy.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: had a chat with @andrea | ocean protocol and we discussed c) briefly. we should probably have a conversation on the future organization of the ambassador program in the light of the growth of regional communities.   different projects handle things differently; polkdadot  for example  have a very coordinated and hierarchical approach  with different heads  handling different regions and/or specialities within the group. this is also what near has been successfully doing.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: this would be something to discuss with @idiom | ocean protocol   @sheridan | ocean protocol   @zippy1979  and @robin | dataunion  and perhaps @brucepon or @trentmc0 as well  with objective to establish a structure for ambassadors doing outreach work.

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: buongiorno @everyone 😃  we are feeling extremely happy to see lot of work coming to fruition. in fact  i am proud to finally announce the official revamp of the ocean protocol ambassador program (opap) 🚀   q4/2021 and beginning of q1/2022 has seen a lot of planning  strategising and executing from every single ambassadors. the vision of the ambassador program is to build an impactful global team  that supports the growth of the ocean protocol ecosystem worldwide and  in order to achieve this  the program needs to be well structured to welcome dozens  if not hundreds  of new ambassadors from each part of the world. this may  in the future  also involve having regional communities operating under the opap umbrella.   keeping our vision and needs in mind  the new program restructuring is now complete. i want to thank all ambassadors and ocean core team for their commitment to the program. particularly i want to personally thank @lrt  @robin | dataunion   @blockchainlugano and @zippy1979 for supporting us in making this possible.   today i'm excited to announce:  - a revamped workspace to allow better coordination amongst ambassadors. the workspace is hosted on notion  a tool that promotes team work and transparency. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/welcome-aboard-cc9dbe2acbf44908aa7e8aa712a2b9f9  - a revamped onboarding process  where candidates will be guided through the ambassador website (work in progress: http://oceanambassadors.community) -> ocean 101 -> and eventually invited to an onboarding video call scheduled each week.  - the introduction of "activity farming". a smooth and efficient process for each ambassador to actively contribute to preapproved activities supporting opf  and get rewarded based on two criteria: the deliverable itself & performance. more details here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1r-ng2vjvicg_a3cuk9fph2queaoyzhrwnyzyhvouu4m/edit?usp=sharing  - an experimental reputation system that helps to promote engagement  increased contributions and team working within the opap. this system allows ambassadors to earn xp based on their contribution to the program - helping them stand out in our new ambassador leaderboard. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/leaderboard-f24b2461b60f4ce1970b255f7dd8767f  - oceanacropolis. an open space for each ambassador to showcase their work  giving them (and everyone else) visibility across social media channels such as twitter. more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/oceanacropolis-750c110a7a234a7e86f577e7431f573c  - a revised reward system to promote fairness  transparency  and to incentivise high-quality work. we have introduced a mix of basic rewards and performance rewards. again  more details here: https://oceanambassadors.notion.site/ocean-rewards-e803515ecda54c1f8fa5200af0343d40  - an open calendar where to find all opap meetings. as agreed with @idiom | ocean protocol  all future ambassadors meetings going forward will be publicly held in the #ambassadors wg. more details here: https://www.notion.so/oceanambassadors/ff179fec09014037b29ac1bce067080a?v=47d781c17e0e426cafc48623f9398688  - an awesome video for everyone to quickly learn about ocean protocol and familiarise with the data economy. sneak peek coming asap.   last but not least  we have also been working on our first ambassadordao. however  this is still work in progress and shan’t reveal more at this time 🤐   plenty more is in the pipeline  and we're all looking forward to seeing what 2022 has for us!  #theyearofadoption  happy farming! 👩‍🌾👨‍🌾 ❤️   andrea

CONTENT: question follow ambassadors: isn't synesis one (p2e ai game) on solana  a 'centralized' platform?

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: i read their whitepaper - it somehow lets people retain their annotations as nfts. but i am very technical and really did not understand how and why that should work. this looks like a lot of marketing for me.  i also do not at all understand why a project that a co-founder of ocean invested in makes it into the ocean protocol news stream. there is no endorsement of ocean protocol and ocean also does not appear anywhere in their whitepaper or technical specs.  nonetheless this is interesting to see as it is very similar to what we are building with dataunion  we just have a different approach 🙂 so far they have 0 p2e games  this is just marketing.

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: thanks for basically letting me know not much makes sense as i was reading about it yesterday. agree with not knowing why it made the opf feed...personally i stay away from chains and projects like solana and it doesn't jive with my view of eth or decentralization. though i'm well aware there are those who will tell me eth is not decentralized. :pepeghostface:

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: it is kind of a data union around nlp data  so this is amazing from my point of view 🙂 but i am also not convinced yet of solana but my developers told me about it/held it when it was at 5$. should have listened to them back then.

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: my 2 ocean on the discussion (or do we have a 'cent' version of ocean yet?)  starting off with a general funda (feel free to critique).  for a p2e concept to work on the current concept  and to interface with a convenient crypto-network component it has to be with a chain that doesn't disturb the end-user in anyway right?  so essentially that has to function with a network that is conducive for faster txns and lower fee  so from my birds eye view i see that polygon  solana are really popular on that front ~ which has happened as a result of marketing of course. might be a reason why we have so many p2e games from a few suspect chains as a function of marketing/ecosystem push.  do you have any line of thoughts to this @robin | dataunion on what you're developing?

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: yeah  we are going to work with polygon as we are using ocean protocol tech. but also looking at celo (mobile first proof of stake  eco friendly chain) and everything else where ocean protocol is available (e.g. kusama  polkadot via moonbeam). we are suffering from having our pool on ethereum mainnet for a long time now and will change that very soon when v4 comes out 🙂

AUTHOR: drprk.eth
CONTENT: cool that's great to know. so i suppose at the end of the day when you're thinking of p2e project you'd only be looking at how users engage or would that be something that has to be very exclusive from a particular ecosystem

AUTHOR: robinlehmann
CONTENT: no  in the end it is important that they have an identity in the form of a wallet or a ssi identity but also the option to receive part of the value being created from the p2e project they are participating in. so we could have chains connected where there is no data asset being offered but the value created is just transfered there from another chain. and our backend is very flexible in regard to the identification scheme used.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: the first article is spot on imo - governance minimization is key. i believe they overstate "consensus" which relates to day-to-day operations and understate "strategic governance" which relates to deep gov redesign  vision or objective changes of the systems when needed.   the gitcoin presentation is fascinating. i wish someone old these guys that data should be expressed in % terms rather than absolute number of survey respondents.. but it doesn't change the value of the insights gathered. brilliant. i think we can relate to this comment re pain points "the biggest pain point are people who want to help but need to be helped to be able to help 🙂 so  for now only very assertive people find something to do."

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: the fei protocol article provides some interesting thoughts on a particular implementation of "optimistic governance". our intended implementation in "activity farming" is more flat  and is handled "after-the-facts"   this means that ***requests for $ocean rewards are made by the ambassador working on an activity only once the activity has been delivered or once the activity performance can be attested. activities do not need to be pre-aligned*** prior to working on them  as long as they are in our activity farming list  and the deliverable complies with our ambassador pledge.  upon submission  ***by default activities are approved and paid***. if another ambassador has doubts and wants to review the activity  the reviewing ambassador should state so  which will trigger a review process in which ambassadors should discuss and conclude whether the activity should be paid or not.

AUTHOR: lrt8723
CONTENT: more on optimistic governance: https://docs.gyro.finance/governance/primitives/optimistic-approval and https://ournetwork.substack.com/p/our-network-deep-dive-2 --- this is all based on web3 stacks  but we could learn faster by handling things off-chain  iterating fast to learn and implementing on-chain when a solution makes sense.   we don't really have much to fear about gev exploits as we will most likely never have deep pockets  and our purpose is not monetary. but of course we want to avoid as many obvious flaws in our governance processes as possible

AUTHOR: nosedive2moon
CONTENT: hi ambassador - i made a proposal to change the reward structure for translation articles and put it into activity farming at the moment its 30$ base reward for articles > 500 words and 1000$ base reward for articles > 1000 words.   the problem is : the most interesting and relevant articles from op are mainly above 1500 - 2000 words. but at the moment the work/reward ratio for articles slightly above 1000 words is the best. so the motivation to translate that kind of articles instead of the ones that are much more interesting & relevant is much higher. by raising the reward for this the motivation to translate that articles will rise.   i suggest adding 3 categories according to the work load:   > 1500 words = 150 usd base rewards + 450 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month > 2000 words = 200 usd base rewards + 600 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month > 2500 words = 250 usd base rewards + 750 usd bonus rewards for 1k impressions within 3 month

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: 📚  **easy poll - quick guide** 📚   - with the /poll command you can easily create polls. normal polls have no time limit. a poll can be either a simple yes/no poll or a poll with up to 20 custom answers. when you create a poll  you can choose who is allowed to vote  - with the /timepoll command you can easily create polls with time limit. in this case a poll can run for a maximum of 7 days.  **useful commands to use: **  allowedrole - to restrict voting to certain roles  text - to add a long description  perhaps to give context and introduce the reason of the poll time - to set a time limit to the poll  **note:**  - you can only create a poll if you're an admin  or have been given the pollcreator role - to create polls in private channels  go to channel -> permissions -> add role -> easypoll

AUTHOR: zippy1979
CONTENT: 🚨 @ambassador 🚨  hello opap friends   the oceandao reconcilliation is now complete and we did not make the funding this round despite attracting more than 1.3m votes. this again means that we will need to pause the activity farming until we can resolve the funding issue. i personally will not be drawing any rewards  until this issue is resolved. everything else needs to be paused (other than twitter which we need to maintain for visibility and growth). for the activities already submitted we will review them in the month end activity farming review as usual  however how the treasury will be dispersed  will need to be voted on by the members of opap. i will ask that when you cast your votes you consider the long term health of the program rather than short term personal gains.  i am in discussions with our advisors how best to handle this situation going forward  applying for funds in every single oceandao funding round rather than once per quarter  is not a sustainable funding model for an ambassadors program. we will need to make changes no matter what.  how we address this and create a sustainable funding model will be worked on and shared with you for comment and then pushed forward. anyone who wishes to help with this process is welcome to reach out to myself or @blockchainlugano  and your input will be appreciated.

AUTHOR: kitblake
CONTENT: @igor k and @zamirana  thanks for your reactions! i see now that giving the main character the same first name as the ukrainian president may not have been amusing and proved a distraction. so i’ve changed the name. but i haven’t used alice or bob. here’s the thinking.  that wikipedia article was illuminating. i wasn’t thrilled with alice or bob because they have personalities. now i’ve learned that their personalities were defined in an "after dinner speech" in 1984. the main character of our user story doesn’t fit those personalities. he’s a developer type.  since those early days more characters have been added to the alice & bob story. there’s eve  who’s an eavesdropper  and mallory  who’s malicious. there’s also “ivan the honourable” who was invented in 2002.  'ivan' is a fitting name for a dev. it connotes the right mindset. someone who’s honourable and concerned about the quality of the code. the name is also not tied to any specific country. could even be american  like alice & bob are.  thus the main character in our user story is now ivan  and i think it’s a real improvement. thanks for your feedback  it proved valuable. 🙏

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: ok team  we took  time to go through the bounties delivered last week. really chewed on this which is why today is wednesday and normally this is done by monday  but i am remaining shellshocked that 95% of the work put in is simply incorrect or incoherent  some on a large scale. none of you will win bounties this way  so imo really read and ask questions to understand how this works  or you will be wasting your precious time for zero reward:  here is an example  see if you can spot an issue  and this is taken from the top 2 threads submitted (good job btw  because it is nearly there!).  part of a posted thread:  ocean templates is an open-source toolkit from @oceanprotocol that provides a complete answer to common issues experienced in #blockchain dapp development.   reasoning this is not of useable quality:  ocean protocol does provide a set of tools and infrastructure to help developers build decentralized applications (dapps) centered around data marketplaces. this includes the usage of templates that *facilitate* standardized data exchange agreements.  however  it's important to note that ocean protocol and its tools are specifically tailored to data sharing  buying  and selling use-cases. they may not address all the "common issues" experienced in general blockchain dapp development  but they do indeed provide significant benefits for those particular use-cases.  with that in mind  a more accurate statement might be:  ocean templates  part of the @oceanprotocol toolkit  provides a comprehensive solution to common challenges experienced in blockchain-based data marketplace development. this thread will inform developers how it can reduce complications and accelerate time-to-market for developing data-centric dapps.  :opapshield: **always be sure to research the specific functionalities and scope of a particular toolkit or platform before making broad claims about its applicability and benefits.**

AUTHOR: beason82
CONTENT: i have a friend who works in data protection who says this is incorrect:  "so it's 'special category data' that's afforded extra protection and where the data is 'stored' is irrelevant  it's where it is 'processed'. also gdpr doesn't require data to stay on 'european soil'  gdpr applies to the 'eu' and there are jurisdictions which are afforded 'adequacy' that are outside of the 'eu'. there are circumstances where you could transfer special category data outside of the eu if you have the appropriate mechanisms in place"

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: do you think ocean protocol's partnership with moonbeam has had much of an impact? @ambassador   my thoughts on it:   the collaboration with moonbeam network signifies ocean protocol's expansion to the polkadot blockchain. initial integration will empower users to seamlessly "publish  stake  and buy" data within polkadot's ecosystem. assets from both ethereum mainnet and moonbeam will eventually coexist within the ocean market  a platform for data discovery and exchange. enhanced privacy features  network bridging  and liquidity sharing are also on the horizon.  trent mcconaghy  co-founder of ocean protocol  highlights the alignment of ocean's multi-blockchain vision with polkadot's interoperability focus. moonbeam's ethereum compatibility makes it a logical starting point for ocean's polkadot venture.   the moonbeam team is constantly working to simplify the implementation process for ethereum developers who want to migrate to polkadot. ocean protocol chose moonbeam as an extension point because of its unrivaled compatibility. the ocean team can now utilize their existing ethereum smart contracts to access the new and growing polkadot ecosystem.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: also wanted to get on the topic of utu's ai-driven trust infrastructure with ocean ones   utu's ai-driven trust infrastructure will assimilate data providers  consumers  datasets  and entities' interactions to construct comprehensive trust profiles. moreover  ocean users can rate and review these entities  all contributing to a dynamically analyzed trust signal.  this approach elevates trust and transparency within ocean market  minimizing transactional friction. users can seamlessly access quality datasets from reliable providers  utilize data for analysis or stake  and avoid risks like rug pulls  fostering a more secure and reliable ecosystem  furthermore  the utu protocol rewards users for providing precise ratings and reviews while safeguarding their data privacy. collaborating with ocean will streamline the process for utu users to monetize their data on ocean market as data providers. users retain complete authority over shared data  deciding which to monetize and its usage terms.  the partnership aims to facilitate data exchange between their protocols. this entails incorporating publicly-available  on-chain utu data like endorsements into ocean market  procuring relevant ocean market datasets for the utu protocol  and analyzing datasets to generate utu recommendations and insights.

AUTHOR: kreigdk
CONTENT: i think  the collaboration between ocean protocol and moonbeam is important. it helps ocean protocol become part of another blockchain. it gives people more ways to work with data. it also allows them to make bets based on that data. all in all  these are new opportunities for ocean protocol. working with utu is also a good thing. they are using artificial intelligence to help people trust each other when sharing data. so ocean market becomes a place to find safe and quality data. and utu helps users make money from their data on ocean market.

AUTHOR: doteth
CONTENT: hey everyone  just wanted to drop here a little hack for the twitter impression campaign starting tomorrow.   you can try these techniques to farm more impressions 😎  - add hashtags with high viewerships. #ai could be an example  but there are more. check the trending section and see if any of them fits. remember too many hashtags are penalized by x so you want to select them carefully   - replies to posts with high views can be another way to farm impressions   - tagging other accounts can provide more visibility to your post. add context to your post such that it makes sense to tag other companies.  - pin your post to your profile to ensure you gain views every time someone visits your profile  - sharing your tweet on reddit or other social media can hugely increase viewrships  - the timing of your post/comment matters  i’d suggest to try them all to see which one works best for you. there may also be other techniques that i didn’t mention yet.   if you get stuck do let me know! happy weekend 😄

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: @ambassador @elite ambassador   i finalized last weeks postmint rewards. i had to manually adjust for a few things  and scores do not reflect metrics as its impossible to do. so  this is a one off but a lesson here.  *the best performing threads did not win. they should've been kicked out but i left them in the competition  but choosing ocean's own marketplace is a lazy move. the objective was to think outside the box and either find a ecosystem partner or invent one.  *due to not being able to score metrics  the points were arbitrarily awarded  in fairness to following instructions  and then best performing.

AUTHOR: himas.
CONTENT: kick out for what? what a lazy step  i spent 3 hours searching for information that best fits the wording of the question  going through all possible applications. and ocean market fits the theme best; other applications fit the wording worse and do not fulfill some of the conditions presented in the theme.

AUTHOR: himas.
CONTENT: after spending 3 hours searching for an answer to the topic  i get - a lazy step. ocean market fits all theme criteria  unlike other applications

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: well  the build and most obvious use of c2d is the ocean market  which has been tweeted over 4 years ad nauseum. i understand if you feel this was a good choice  and perhaps my wording was sharp. however  the point of being an ambassador is to educate the public and promote the tech space outside the obvious. in fact i did not disqualify the threads  but left them in. ocean market is not the focus on what ocean can do  and we need to push traction and build outside of what is an obvious fallback  c2d was publicly shipped via the marketplace  but there are limitless builds that can be done with the tech.

AUTHOR: himas.
CONTENT: i've only been studying ocean for about 2-3 months and i can't know what was used 4 years ago until then. the predictoor threads   which we have done several times in a row   fall under the same wording . and nothing terrible happened . the question sounded like this : write about a dapp that uses ocean's compute-to-data to create insights out of datasets available and add the use of datatokens to sell insights.           following from the question  you need to write about 1) an application  2) that uses compute-to-data technology   3) create insights out of datasets available   4) add the use of datatokens to sell insights. under all these conditions  of all the applications  ocean market is exclusively suitable   other applications are not fully suitable  since they do not fulfill one or 2 conditions. some do not create insights out of datasets available  some do not sell at all. at the same time  you put threads about the ephemeral use of technology ( which does not fit the topic at all ) . the above thread is about an application that perfectly matches the topic . i might as well have just written about some ocean technologies without reading the topic at all   while not getting the risk of disqualification and accusations of laziness . your criterion - ocean market is not interesting for users  since once upon a time there was a lot of information about it on twitter - is absolutely unfair. i couldn't even know about it in theory. at the same time  ocean market is a very useful  product that is worth attention. and judging by the number of likes  views and interactions  this thread was very interesting to my audience  it showed the best performance in the entire history of my activities.

AUTHOR: himas.
CONTENT: i’m very upset to receive such a low assessment of my work  despite the fact that even more time was spent than on launching predictoor.

AUTHOR: blockchainlugano
CONTENT: i'm not giving a low assessment of work  the thread in itself was good. the adjective used was in reference to choice in dapp. that it is ocean's own seems logical that it would be covered to no end.  i think the wording of the task (write about a dapp that uses ocean's compute-to-data to create insights out of datasets available and add the use of datatokens to sell insights) perhaps was not clear enough  my bad  and it should've been creative and hypothetical. for those who could not do so reverting to something else out there that exists would be a logical step. there are many products using ocean that fall into all the categories  that are using insights via the marketplace or their own. we could go into dimitra  datalatte  ones covered by other ambassadors. etc. we are trying to spotlight ocean tech without being 'ocean' as they have their own twitter account and inhouse marketing team that covers what they are doing better than we ever could.  as per the metrics  i agree you had many. and the 3 hour workload to create this goes along with many other ambassadors who spend similar amounts on their thread. but i could not in good faith award the top tweets to ones that cover in essence what compute-to-data is instead of highlighting the workflow outside of the given pipeline.  dm me if you want to discuss further.

AUTHOR: jb1908
CONTENT: to stake ocean you have first to understand the concept of veocean.  furthermore  you should check out the data farming (df) itself  because around 500m of ocean will be released in that way and it constitute the mechanism for incentives good production and good allocation of high quality data set.  https://docs.oceanprotocol.com/rewards/df-intro  to make it short  but you can also check a thread i made about: locking ocean from 1week to 4years provides you veocean (1 veocean = 1 ocean locked for 4 years). then every week you can earn ocean in two way with veocean: -passive  just holding veocean provide you weekly ocean  -active  you allocate veocean to dataset and earn from that  this is strictly linked to the consume of the dataset. you can also earn actively by participating in data challenges  also then are in active section of df.  lastly  you are lucky because we just entered in df main  after completed some beta phases  now we entered in the core phase of data farming.  https://blog.oceanprotocol.com/ocean-data-farming-main-is-here-49c99602419e   https://twitter.com/jambu1908/status/1637780595945226240?s=46&t=vmnprfnvtvpjegbr81wcsw

CONTENT: not saying that we don’t want price to increase  but the ultimate goal for us (ambassadors)  is to organically grow the awareness about ocean techs and the possibilities utilising them.  said that  i would really like a poker game built on ocean stack   but in my honest opinion it shouldn’t utilise ocean token but a different token or an in-game currency that ofc can be then exchanged with ocean  just not utilising ocean as the in-game currency.   ocean is the currency of the new data economy and should be strictly linked to that  having it as in-game currency would probably dilute ocean value instead of accruing it.   lastly  remember that around 500m ocean token are destined to data farming  thus i would suggest to build a poker game that is directly linked to df where datanft can be created with poker tendencies/spot evaluation/ev+ strategies etc  would definitely help you with that. 💪🏻

AUTHOR: feno1486
CONTENT: compute-to-data offers a unique solution by allowing computations to be performed on sensitive data without the need to centralize or transfer the data itself. this approach preserves data privacy  reduces the risk of breaches  and enables collaboration and analysis across organizations without sacrificing security.  practical examples:  1.medical research and privacy protection if a pharmaceutical company wants to collect patient data from different hospitals  then it would have to request patient data and store it  which would call into question the confidentiality of this data. with compute-to-data  the hospitals can retain control over their data. the pharmaceutical company sends its algorithms to each hospital  where the algorithms run directly on the hospital's premises. the hospital's data remains secure within its own environment  and only aggregated results or insights are shared with the pharmaceutical company  2.financial fraud detection consider a financial consortium that wants to identify patterns of fraudulent transactions across multiple banks. in a conventional approach  all transaction data would need to be shared or centralized  which poses risks of data breaches and unauthorized access.  compute-to-data can be employed here to address these concerns. each bank retains its transaction data and deploys fraud detection algorithms locally. these algorithms analyze the data and identify potential fraud patterns. only aggregated or summarized information about fraudulent patterns is shared with the consortium  without revealing the raw transaction details. this way  individual bank data remains secure  and the consortium still gains valuable insights for fraud prevention.

AUTHOR: denkcryptoo12
CONTENT: ocean protocol serves as an on-chain marketplace for off-chain datasets. each dataset possesses an erc20 datatoken representation on ethereum  used for data access payment and on-chain metadata storage. the encrypted url in the metadata directs to off-chain data storage (e.g.  google drive  ipfs). given this off-chain data approach  ocean protocol is distinct from a blockchain oracle.  ocean protocol and chainlink are synergistic. ocean complements chainlink by offering curated datasets for smart contract consumption through chainlink oracles  enabling seamless integration into various blockchains.

AUTHOR: fakedepression
CONTENT: hey  i have joined only yesterday and have not read all the docs yet but i have some thoughts.  1)imagine a situation where the data marketplace for the ocean protocol dynamically modifies data prices in response to present-day demand or outside variables. the pricing of data assets on the market would be affected by the relevant data that chainlink's oracles could retrieve  such as market trends  user preferences  or economic indicators. for instance  chainlink oracles could offer the necessary external data to adjust the pricing in real-time if a particular dataset becomes highly sought after as a result of an emerging trend or event. 2) smart contracts triggered by weather: chainlink's oracles may make it possible to build ocean protocol smart contracts that are triggered by actual events  like weather conditions. for instance  a user could configure a smart contract to automatically buy weather information from the ocean marketplace the moment rain begins to fall in their city. then  depending on the use  this information might be put to use to modify insurance rates  improve logistics  or set off particular actions in smart home systems.

AUTHOR: fakedepression
CONTENT: 3) data integrity and provenance: by offering real-time attestations and proofs of data integrity  chainlink's oracles could increase the trustworthiness of data assets on the ocean protocol. an uploaded dataset to the ocean marketplace  for instance  could be connected to chainlink oracles that periodically check its integrity and make sure it hasn't been altered. the data would become more trustworthy and valuable to potential buyers as a result of this extra measure of assurance. 4) building on uber/didi example from above  consider how users could integrate real-time user-generated data into the ocean protocol to provide details about traffic jams  road conditions  and other pertinent information. the incorporation of this user-generated data into smart contracts could be made easier by chainlink's oracles  enabling applications like ride-sharing services to dynamically change prices  optimize routes  or improve user experiences based on the most recent information.

AUTHOR: austineking
CONTENT: ocean protocol  as is already known  is a decentralized data exchange protocol that permits data sharing and monetization while protecting anonymity. although ocean protocols already helping with some parts of developing a decentralized social network  many other technological  sociological  and ethical issues need to be addressed to build a suitable and decentralized social network. these issues extend beyond the data interchange layer.  to create such a network  you would have to think about:  decentralization: ensuring that no one organization controls the network's infrastructure  governance  or data.  data privacy is the protection of user data and the provision of control over personal data to users.  censorship resistance: preventing content modification or censorship by any party  including the platform.  even though ocean protocol can offer solutions for data sharing and access   ocean protocol can offer access control and data sharing features  thooceancean is well equipped but it's not a comprehensive approach to creating a decentralized social network. so in my own opinion  to overcome all the aforementioned issues  the ocean protocol would probably need to be used in conjunction with other technologies and strategies. in addition  creating an ideal  equitable  and decentralized social network is a difficult task that also entails legal  moral  and social factors.

CONTENT: this conversation is fascinating  lol. in the modern healthcare system and for one's well-being  health data and biometric tools are essential. the following are some benefits of health data collection:  protecting people's privacy and security requires handling health data and biometric information carefully. the importance of data encryption and adherence to laws like hipaa (in the united states) cannot be overstated. early detection and prevention: health information gathered by biometric sensors  such as glucose meters or heart rate monitors  can assist in the early detection of health disorders. the prompt action and preventive measures made possible by this early discovery   biometric information can be used to personalize medical care and treatment regimens to suit a patient's unique requirements. as a result  therapies are more successful and have fewer side effects.    chronic disease management: for those with long-term diseases like diabetes or hypertension  ongoing biometric data monitoring can help with better disease management and treatment plan adherence.  research and development: for the study of medicine  compiled health information from a sizable population can be very helpful. it can be used to find patterns  risk factors  and prospective hot spots for healthcare innovation. all thanks to ocean protocols  which update all the data and make it monetized  shareable  and as well accessibility.  in summary  health data and biometric devices are instrumental in improving healthcare outcomes  enhancing individual well-being  and advancing medical research and innovation. however  it's important to balance the benefits with privacy and security considerations  💽  💊  🔐

AUTHOR: georgegem
CONTENT: the topic is valid and relevant. but i have a number of questions. 1) i certainly believe that any personal data should belong only to its owner  but the collection of medical data is crucial  because it is the basis for research. if each user will sell the data by setting the price himself  then there may be a situation when the users of the application will overestimate the cost of data  which in the long run will reduce the number of conducted studies because the cost of them will increase.   solution: make it possible for users of health monitoring applications to sell data for a fixed price or not exceeding a certain mathematically set price  or to refuse such a sale  it is also possible to introduce data rental  so medical institutions will pay for subscription to the service  the service will distribute this money among users. excellent mechanics i think  although it still needs to be thought out in more detail!  2) in order to popularize such a platform it is also necessary that there is a demand for this data  if now this data can be collected in other ways and the person does not own his data fully  why should medical institutions (especially research institutions) buy data on the ocean market ?   solution: we need to harmonize the change at the legislative level  i.e. introduce legislation that will prohibit any collection and storage of medical data in unencrypted form. this is quite a long way off  but it is still worth taking this step into the digital future.

AUTHOR: austineking
CONTENT: personal data is very important  for me  the gathering and administration of a person's data is referred to as a self-data pool  also called a personal data pool.   having control over your data may have the following benefits:  privacy control: you are in charge of managing and safeguarding your data  choosing what information to share and with whom. this can reduce worries about privacy.  data security: by putting strong security measures in place  you can guard your data from breaches and illegal access.  data monetization: in some circumstances  you can decide to share your data only with certain parties and even make money off of it by selling it to businesses or taking part in data-sharing initiatives.  customization: by making the data pool specifically for your needs  you can make sure that it contains information pertinent to your interests and way of life.  data security: to prevent unwanted access to your data  you can put in place strong security measures.  data monetization: in certain circumstances  you may decide to give or sell your data to businesses or researchers to gain financial gain.  it's crucial to keep in mind that maintaining a self-data pool has obligations  particularly those related to data security and privacy. encryption  backups  and compliance with data protection laws must all be done properly to maximize benefits and reduce dangers.  💽  💻 🔐 🛃

AUTHOR: georgegem
CONTENT: ocean protocol really solves a lot of problems on vision and data transmission. therefore  your question is important. i will answer each of them in order.  1) data transmission and low latency: ocean protocol has created a decentralized system for data transmission  data is not transmitted by itself  ocean protocol does not store it  it is stored in other data providers like ipfs  github and others. thus ocean protocol allows you to create a datatoken that gives access to data by means of a link to this data in third-party storage services. therefore  the speed of data transfer is quite high  because you do not transfer the data itself  but only access to it with the help of a token. since the base of the protocol is a blockchain  the delay will be minimal because not too much data is transferred.  2) data security and confidentiality: ocean protocol incorporates encryption techniques  access control mechanisms  and privacy-preserving technologies. as already mentioned data is transmitted in the form of urls  but all these links are securely encrypted  it is not possible to access the link (to the data on this link) if you have not purchased access to the data. in addition  for especially important data that must remain confidential there is a special service c2d  so the data provider provides access not to the data itself but to algorithms over the data set and can control the disclosed data and its parameters. for example: if there is a set of medical data  using the c2d service it is possible to sell data calculations  i.e. the buyer will get for example the number of patients or the average age of a certain group of patients  etc.  but he will not get any confidential data from this set  what he will get directly depends on the algorithm used. in addition  after the data computation is done  only the log and the results that the algorithm created are returned  and the set itself and the algorithm are deleted  which ensures the confidentiality of the data.

AUTHOR: georgegem
CONTENT: 3) scalability and resource management: ocean protocol employs distributed storage solutions  including ipfs (interplanetary file system) and decentralized databases like oceandb. these technologies allow data to be distributed across multiple nodes and scaled as needed. data sharding and partitioning techniques may also be used to optimize storage and retrieval. furthermore  decentralized resource allocation mechanisms  such as blockchain-based token incentives  help manage resources efficiently.  4) regarding data availability and reliability  i can't answer this question as i haven't found any information about it. but i can assume that replication and backup strategies can be used to ensure data availability  but again they are used in decentralized databases  and ocean protocol does not store data  this task is handled by third-party services and databases.

AUTHOR: austineking
CONTENT: data 💽 availability and network reliability are very important in ocean protocols  enabling trustworthy and resilient data sharing in the field of ocean protocols and related domains.  so  to ensure high data availability and network reliability in ocean protocols  we need to be observative in the following database technology  ☎️   data replication: in a network  data is frequently copied across several nodes. due to this redundancy  the data is kept accessible even if some nodes go down.  incentive mechanisms: to motivate network users to provide dependable data hosting and maintenance  many ocean protocols include token incentives. this encourages data suppliers to guarantee high availability.  data provenance: keeping a record of the data's provenance  which includes its origin and history  aids in building confidence in the data. this openness improves the data's dependability.  disaster recovery: robust disaster recovery plans are essential to deal with unexpected outages or data loss. this might involve regular data backups and redundancy measures. so i think 🤔 and suggesting that the above point will help a lot in data availability and reliability in ocean protocol.

result to straining ocean protocol capacity  thus resulting in slowing down data retrieval and processing of such date. security threat: it’s prominent to note that large datasets are attractive targets for cyberattacks. therefore resulting to data breach  data theft or even data manipulation.  depreciation of decentralization: maintaining decentralization while handling vast data volumes is challenging. in other words  handling vast amounts of data may lead to compromise in the decentralized nature of ocean protocol.   the fore mentioned challenges are the well notable complexities i believe ocean protocol can face while working with vast volume of data.   nevertheless  ocean protocol has tackled this possible complexities that can arise while working with vast volumes of data through the following technologies:  blockchain technology: with the adoption of blockchain technology  particularly ethereum  which provides security through its decentralized and immutable ledger  ocean protocol have tackled the issue of security threat. transactions and data shared on the ocean protocol blockchain are cryptographically secured. thus  enhancing data security.  however  scalability can be a challenge on some blockchain networks  which is why ocean protocol explores layer 2 solutions and other optimizations which improved scalability significantly in relation to working with vast volume of date. c2d:  with the adoption and implementation of c2d  ocean protocol have prevented sensitive data from being exposed during computation  improving security while also potentially reducing the need for extensive data transfer. therefore  contributing to scalability. data nfts and datatokens: the introduction of data nfts and customized datatoken contracts has played a huge role in tackling scalability issue. the former and the latter has provided more flexibility and control over licensing arrangements. this flexibility has significantly contributed to scalability by accommodating different use cases and business models  thus attracting a wider user base. these technologies have addressed aspects of both security and scalability. thus achieving a robust security and high scalability in a decentralized data sharing manner.   question 2:  regarding to the question: how does one ensure fast data transmission and low latency when exchanging data among participants?  one can tackle this challenge by making sure that the foundational systems  such as networks  storage  e.t.c  can easily grow sideways to handle more and more data. for example  ocean protocol adopted gen x modular framework which aided to maintain fast and efficient data exchange which aligns with my idea of scalable infrastructure.  relating to the question: how is the secure storage and transmission of sensitive data ensured  considering potential security and confidentiality threats?  ocean protocol adopted a decentralized architecture which spreads data across multiple nodes  thus reducing the risk of an unauthorized access. moreover  since data is not stored in a centralized archive  it is hard for malicious actors to target a single location. lastly   ocean protocol utilizes erc 20 datatokens to represent ownership and access rights for specific datasets. these tokens aid to secure and standardize data trading within ocean protocol ecosystem.   question 3  as i mentioned earlier in response to question 1  ocean protocol effectively addresses the scalability challenge through the adoption and implementation of various technologies. these technical innovation include blockchain technology  c2d  data nfts  and data tokens. these innovations collectively optimize data storage and transmission in a decentralized environment  ensuring efficient resource management.

CONTENT: general answer about importance   democratizing data with ocean protocol  ocean protocol has a clear mission: to democratize data by leveraging technology and governance  leading to more equitable outcomes. to truly understand the importance of this mission  let's take a deeper dive into the realm of data.  in today's digital landscape  we often encounter meticulously timed and targeted advertisements on our screens. these ads are possible due to extensive data collection from various sources such as social media activity or website browsing history. however  it is disheartening that only a select few companies reap significant profits from this valuable resource—data.  moreover  concerns around privacy loom large in relation to data collection practices. many users worry about their personal information being harvested without informed consent for financial gains made by third parties. in fact  recent instances like france fining tech giants google and facebook highlight these apprehensions where user tracking was conducted against individual preferences.  data holds immense value; its potential profitability cannot be understated. nevertheless  maintaining control over one's own information while ensuring privacy remains an ongoing challenge—a predicament deserving attention given how little profit typically trickles down towards those who actually generate the underlying dataset themselves—the owners of said-data.  this is precisely where ocean protocol steps in as an innovative solution provider—an avenue aimed at enhancing transparency within the world of big data through blockchain implementation.

AUTHOR: crox_verse
CONTENT: very important topic to discuss about  data nfts and datatokens ocean simplifies the process of publishing and consuming data services in the decentralized finance (defi) space. with ocean  users can deploy erc721 data nfts and erc20 datatokens  turning crypto wallets  exchanges  and daos into data wallets  exchanges  and daos.  data nfts and datatokens serve as the connection between data assets and blockchain/defi tools. this allows for the creation of data wallets  data marketplaces  data co-ops  and more through defi composability. the actual data does not need to be stored on-chain  only the access control.  ocean-based apps make it easy for end users to access and interact with data assets  while ocean smart contracts and libraries simplify the development process for developers.  data nfts represent ownership of a unique asset using the erc721 standard  while datatokens repurpose erc20 crypto wallets as data wallets and crypto exchanges as data marketplaces.  by bridging the data industry with defi assets under management  datatokens bring more value to the defi space by optimizing yields and capital efficiency.  decentralized access control is combined with a user-friendly experience for both developers and users.  how it works data nfts are erc721 tokens that represent unique assets  while datatokens are erc20 tokens used to access data services. each data service has its own data nft and one or more types of datatokens.  to access a dataset  you need to hold 1.0 datatokens.  to grant someone else access to a dataset  you simply send them 1.0 datatokens. it's as simple as that.  since datatokens are erc20 tokens on the ethereum mainnet  they can leverage the entire ecosystem built around erc20 tokens.

AUTHOR: crox_verse
CONTENT: ocean market use ocean market to publish your own datatokens  buy/sell datatokens  or consume datatokens.  ocean datatokens: from money legos to data legos: how defi helps data  and data helps defi datatokens 1: data custody. data access control meets crypto wallets and data daos. datatokens 2: non-fungible  fungible and composable datatokens. for data baskets  limited-edition datasets  priced compute pipelines  and more. datatokens 3: data and decentralized finance (data * defi). data as collateral. data dexes  data loans  data stablecoins  and datatokens in financial supply chains

CONTENT: the **compute-to-data**  is a truly unique feature  which goes a long way to tell the general public how customer-worthy ocean protocol really is by always putting their users privacy first. this function didn't always exist but with developing times it became evident that this function was a necessity. the **compute-to-data** function allows data remain on-chain while enabling 3rd parties to perform computations on said data. this ensures that sensitive information remains confidential.

AUTHOR: vitusdaniel1
CONTENT: think of **compute-to-data** in the ocean protocol ecosystem as a way to work on a jigsaw puzzle without revealing the whole picture to someone else. you have a puzzle  and someone else has some missing pieces. instead of giving them your entire puzzle  you allow them to place their missing pieces in your puzzle in a secure way  and they can see only the parts that are relevant to them. this way  you collaborate on the puzzle without exposing the complete picture  ensuring data privacy and security. a win-win for everybody 💯🌍

AUTHOR: hopper255
CONTENT: hi friends  data protection is a very important topic today  especially considering how much information is collected about us. but how do we make sure that big companies really care about our private information? sometimes it's unclear.  here's the key thing: compute-to-data technology can help solve this problem. this method allows you to make money from sensitive data without revealing it. instead of selling the data itself  you provide access to it for processing. for example  if you have medical records  you can allow an algorithm to run to calculate the average age of patients  but no other details are disclosed.  this method helps strike a balance between using the data and protecting it. you keep it  but third parties can perform certain calculations on it  such as statistical analysis or artificial intelligence development.  private data is valuable but difficult to monetise because of privacy issues. compute-to-data solves this problem by providing access to data without directly exposing it. this is useful in research  technology development  and data markets.

AUTHOR: crox_verse
CONTENT: my summary on data nfts provides a comprehensive understanding of their significance in the digital world. nfts  or non-fungible tokens  have gained popularity as a means to tokenize and authenticate unique digital assets. they have primarily been associated with artwork and collectibles  but the concept can extend to data as well.  if i were to create a data nft  i would focus on personal health data. with increasing emphasis on wellness and self-care  individuals are generating vast amounts of health-related data through wearables  fitness apps  and medical devices. this data holds immense value for individuals  healthcare providers  and researchers. by creating a data nft for personal health information  individuals could retain ownership and control over their data while also having the option to sell or license it securely.  such a data nft could empower individuals to monetize their own health data  allowing them to choose who has access and potentially contributing to medical research advancements. additionally  it could establish a transparent and traceable system for data sharing  ensuring privacy and security while fostering innovation.  in conclusion  creating a data nft centered around personal health data would not only enable individuals to benefit from their own information but also contribute to the broader healthcare ecosystem.

AUTHOR: austineking
CONTENT: for several reasons  such as the advancement of ai and medical research  a high-quality data source marketplace is necessary. for the following reasons  data diversity: a marketplace of this kind might provide a wide range of data sources  giving researchers and developers access to a wide range of datasets that are essential for building ai models and performing in-depth medical research.  data quality: both ai and medical research depend on high-quality data. a marketplace can validate and curate datasets  lowering the chance of using unreliable or skewed data.  cost-efficiency: data can be acquired economically through the use of a market. by purchasing data from a reputable marketplace  researchers and ai developers can avoid the significant costs related to data collecting and cleaning.  accessibility: it improves data accessibility  democratizing access for smaller research teams or businesses who may lack the means to individually compile huge datasets.

CONTENT: very nice  is good to discuss about this ai have impacted greatly in human activities.   ai creativity can have both positive and negative impacts on human creativity. here are some key points to consider:  collaboration and inspiration: human creators of art  music  and literature can draw inspiration from ai-generated works. artists  musicians  and authors can work with ai systems to improve their creative processes or use ai-generated content as a starting point.  efficiency and automation: artificial intelligence (ai) tools can automate tedious and time-consuming processes  freeing up human producers to concentrate more on the imaginative and original components of their work. this may result in greater output and the investigation of fresh creative concepts.  exploration of new frontiers: ai can push the limits of creativity by producing original and out-of-the-box ideas that people might not have come up with on their own. this may provide new opportunities for human creativity and promote experimentation.  negative impact  dependence and stagnation: a reliance that is too great on ai-generated material may result in a decline in human creativity. the ability of producers to generate ideas and material may stagnate or decline if they rely too heavily on ai.  originality and authenticity: artificial intelligence-generated content might not have the same depth of emotional and personal experiences as human producers do. this can lead to creative works like music  painting  or literature that appear technically accomplished but lack the authenticity and originality that come from human creation.
